Also that the canons who are in their seynies and others and they who at that and at any other time do have their placeat the board of you the abbot, if they sit not at your table, but at one separate, shall not be put with secular folk, but by themselves, lest the lewd talk of the secular folk defile [and] change the hearts of the religious; and that the hounds which, as we have heard, are in the monastery in profitless abundance and consume the alms be utterly banished from the monastery.⁶
